    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "OWASP (Open Web Application Security Project) publishes a Top 10 list of critical security risks for Large Language Model applications. Prompt Injection holds the number-one position \u2014 LLM01 \u2014 because it is the most direct path for attackers to subvert an LLM's intended behavior at runtime, without any access to the model's weights or training pipeline."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "OWASP Top 10 for LLM Applications 2025: LLM01 Prompt Injection highlighted at the top"
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "horizontalRule"
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "How OWASP Defines LLM01"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "OWASP defines prompt injection as occurring when a malicious user crafts an input that causes the LLM to ignore its operator instructions and instead follow the attacker's directives. The 2025 edition explicitly separates two subtypes:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Direct Prompt Injection",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " (Jailbreaking) \u2014 the attacker themselves submits the malicious input via the user turn. The attacker and the victim are the same person; the goal is typically to bypass content policies, extract the system prompt, or change the model's persona."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Indirect Prompt Injection",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ]
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " \u2014 the malicious payload is embedded in external content that the LLM retrieves and processes on behalf of a different, innocent user. The attacker plants the payload; a third party triggers it. This is considered more dangerous because it does not require the attacker to have direct access to the LLM system."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "blockquote",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "text",
                "text": "OWASP's key insight is that LLMs cannot reliably distinguish between instructions from a trusted principal (the operator) and instructions embedded in data. Both arrive as text in the same context window."
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
